<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-01-07T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-01-07T19:00:00-05:00" n="25" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d25">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">710.Consultation 3/248: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Colombia</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Braden</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Bogotá</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-01-07T19:00:00-05:00">January 7, 1942—7
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 10:19 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>23. For the Under Secretary. My telegram No. 18 of January 5, 11
                                p.m.<note n="61" xml:id="d25fn61">Not printed.</note> In response to
                            my inquiry Minister of Foreign Relations this morning had no further
                            information except his belief if [<hi rend="italic">is</hi>] that
                            resistance to a resolution calling on all American Republics to break
                            relations with the Axis would take as juridical basis, “false though it
                            be,” the thesis that the aggression had been committed against islands
                            outside this hemisphere.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Braden</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>